Now that [compression](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/apigateway/latest/developerguide/api-gateway-gzip-compression-decompression.html) has been released for api gateway, it would be great if there was some way configure it from Chalice. My proposal is to add an optional configuration parameter of `minimum_compression_size` to each stage in the `config.json` file. This would look something like:
```javascript
{
  "version": "2.0",
  "app_name": "compression-poc"
  "stages": {
    "dev": {
      "api_gateway_stage": "api",
      "minimum_compression_size": 0,
      "lambda_memory_size": 1536
    }
  }
}
```

In both the options.set and options.get, the names and values should be stripped.

There are many cases (such as SENTRY_DSN) that a whitespace in front or at the end of the string raises an error code 500 for invalid uri format.

https://github.com/APSL/django-kaio/blob/master/kaio/options.py#L138

```python
    def set(self, name, value, section=DEFAULT_SECTION):
        if type(value) == str:
            value = value.decode('utf-8')
        if name in self.options:
            self.options[name].value = value
        else:
            self.options[name] = Option(value, section)

    def get(self, name, default=None, section=DEFAULT_SECTION):
        """Returns value, and also saves the requested default
        If value exists in environ, return environ value"""

        try:
            self.options[name].default_value = default
            if not self.options[name].section:
                self.options[name].section = section
        except KeyError:
            self.options[name] = Option(value=None, section=section,
                   default_value=default)
```

Using python2.7 and pyjnius to develop an Android App. I am implementing a JAVA interface class android.bluetooth.le.ScanCallback for BLE support. Whenever I try to instantiate the python class it gives an error "JVM error: android.bluetooth.le.ScanCallback is not an abstract class". I have checked the documentation and android.bluetooth.le.ScanCallback is an abstract class.  
Here is my code which implements the abstract Java class. 

class ScanCallback(PythonJavaClass):
	__javainterfaces__ = ['android/bluetooth/le/ScanCallback'] 
	def __init__(self, scanCallback, batchCallback=None, errorCallback=None):
		super(ScanCallback, self).__init__()
		self.batchCallbk = batchCallback
		self.scanCallbk = scanCallback
		self.errorCallbk = errorCallback
		pass
	@java_method ('(L/java/utils/List<ScanResult>/)V')
	def onBatchScanResults(self,results): 
	 	print dir(results)
	@java_method ('(I)V') 	
	def onScanFailed(self, errorCode):
		print "failed to scan" + str(errorCode)
		raise ValueError(str(errorCode))
	
	@java_method ('(IL/android/bluetooth/le/ScanResult)V')
	def onScanResult(self, callbackType, result):
		print dir(result)

The purpose of --override-channels is to use only the channels specified at the command line, so it should not include <unknown> packages. This is particularly annoying if you are just trying to list the packages from a binstar channel with `conda search -c username --override-channels`.

<!---
@huboard:{"order":1.9563750449481093e-28,"custom_state":""}
-->

Method log2 is not available on Android before API 18, so fast_log.h is not compilable for older Android.

The suggestion is to update the row

```
#if defined(_MSC_VER) && _MSC_VER <= 1700
  // Visual Studio 2012 does not have the log2() function defined, so we use
  // log() and a multiplication instead.
```

to

```
#if (defined(__ANDROID_API__) && __ANDROID_API__ <= 17) || (defined(_MSC_VER) && _MSC_VER <= 1700)
  // Old Android API 17 and old Visual Studio 2012 do not have the log2() function defined, so we use
  // log() and a multiplication instead.
```

I would appreciate some help with fixing problems caused by hidden symbol visibility. We built a large code base for linux and macOS with an older version of pybind11 that uses a separate wrapper file for each class (more or less). We are now having problems when we try to build with pybind11 2.2.3 with symbols hidden (something we never tried before).

The current problem I'm wrestling with is that type_info for a given object is different depending on which module I obtain the type info from. But only on macOS, not linux. I *suspect* this means I have to export the symbol for the class in question from the module where it is wrapped, so other wrappers can see it (if only because it all works fine if I don't hide symbols). Here is the simplest example I have been able to come up with:

pb.h:
```
#ifndef LSST_PB
#define LSST_PB

#include <typeinfo>

class ClassA {
public:
    ClassA(void){};

    std::type_info const& type_a() const { return (typeid(ClassA)); };
};

class ClassB {
public:
    ClassB(void){};

    ~ClassB(void) = default;

    std::type_info const& type_a() const { return (typeid(ClassA)); };
};

#endif
```

a.cc
```
#include "pybind11/pybind11.h"
#include "pb.h"
namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_MODULE(a, mod) {
    py::class_<std::type_info>(mod, "TypeInfo")
            .def("__eq__",
                 [](std::type_info const& self, std::type_info const& other) { return self == other; })
            .def("__ne__",
                 [](std::type_info const& self, std::type_info const& other) { return self != other; })
            .def("name", &std::type_info::name)
            .def("hash_code", &std::type_info::hash_code);

    py::class_<ClassA, std::shared_ptr<ClassA>> cls(mod, "ClassA");
    cls.def(py::init<>());
    cls.def("type_a", &ClassA::type_a, py::return_value_policy::reference);
}
```

b.h
```
#include "pybind11/pybind11.h"
#include "pb.h"
namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_MODULE(b, mod) {
    py::module::import("a");

    py::class_<ClassB, std::shared_ptr<ClassB>> cls(mod, "ClassB");
    cls.def(py::init<>());
    cls.def("type_a", &ClassB::type_a, py::return_value_policy::reference);
}
```

Put these all in a directory "src" and use this CMakeLists.txt:

```
cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 2.8.12)
project(pb)

add_subdirectory(pybind11)
pybind11_add_module(a src/a.cc)
pybind11_add_module(b src/b.cc)
```

It builds just fine (though I've seen situation where `py::module::import("a");` segfaults on import of the module `b` and I'm not sure why -- it's not random, but small changes to the build seem to make this happen).

If I then run Python and create an instance of ClassA and ClassB I see is that the value returned by `type_a()` is different for the two instances: they do not compare equal.

My suspicion is that I have to export `ClassA` from the module `a` so that the module `b` can see it. I just don't know how to do that. The documentation recommends PYBIND11_EXPORT as part of the class definition, and I have tried that in the definition of `ClassA` but it has no effect. Also our C++ is used as shared libraries by other code, so I don't want to add pybind11-specific code to that; we strongly prefer to isolate the pybind11 wrappers from the C++ code it wraps. Thus a solution that is specific to the wrappers would be most appreciated.

