I realized recently that SAM does not error when I add an API Event to a function for a path that is not defined explicitly in my Swagger file.

In the example below, "/add" path is defined in Events but not in the Swagger spec. It means, SAM will add a AWS::Lambda::Permission resource to allow APIGW to invoke "/add" but this API is not even created in the first place. 

We need to detect this scenario and fail fast. It will provide a tighter semantic validation.

```
Resources:
  MyFunction:
    Type: AWS::Serverless::Function
    Properties:
      CodeUri: s3://bucket/code.zip
      Handler: index.restapi
      Runtime: nodejs4.3
      Events:
        AddApi:
          Type: Api
          Properties:
            # /add is NOT present in the Swagger.
            Path: /add
            Method: post
            RestApiId: ApiWithInlineSwagger


  ApiWithInlineSwagger:
    Type: AWS::Serverless::Api
    Properties:
      StageName: Prod
      DefinitionBody: {
          "info": {
            "version": "1.0",
            "title": {
              "Ref": "AWS::StackName"
            }
          },
          "paths": {
            "/foo": {
              "x-amazon-apigateway-any-method": {
                "x-amazon-apigateway-integration": {
                  "httpMethod": "POST",
                  "type": "aws_proxy",
                  "uri": {
                    "Fn::Sub": "arn:aws:apigateway:${AWS::Region}:lambda:path/2015-03-31/functions/${MyFunction.Arn}/invocations"
                  }
                },
                "responses": {}
              }
            }
          },
          "swagger": "2.0"
        }
```

